Intention is essential to iniuria : ‘pati quis iniuriam etiamsi non sentiat potest, facere nemo, nisi qui scit se iniuriam facere, etiamsi nesciat cui faciat' Dig. 47. ιο. 3. 2 ; hence those were held incapable of committing iniuria who could not have such intention, e. g. persons of weat or un- sound mind, and children not yet doli capaces.

θ 1. The second condition of iniuria is an overt act, which, as is said in the text, might be directed against the person or the reputation:

' ‘iniuriam autem fieri Labeo ait aut re, aut verbis: re, quotiens manus inferuntur, verbis autem, quotiens non manus inferuntur, convicium fit: omnemque iniuriam aut in corpus inferri, aut ad dignitatem aut ad infamiam pertinere' Dig. 47. ro 1. 1 and 2. Among acts which amount to iniuria, besides those mentioned in the text, are calling upon sureties · to discharge a debt which the debtor is quite able and willing to pay himself, Dig. ib. 19 and 203 offering for sale another’s property under the pretence that one has a mongage over it, ib. 15. 32 and 33; the publication of a will whose provisions one should have kept secret, Dig. 9. 2. 4ι. pr.; unwarranted entry upon another man's dwelliug against his will, Dig. 47. 10. 5. pr.; hindering another in the use of a ‘res publico usui destinata' ib. 13. 7, and unjustifiable questioning of another's status, ib. 11. 9.
